Viljoen Kallis Voges syndrome, also known as microcephaly-brachydactyly-kyphoscoliosis syndrome, is a very rare genetic disorder which is characterized by severe intellectual disabilities, microcephaly, low height, brachydactyly type D, flat occiput, down-slanting parpebral fissures, low-set prominent ears, a broad nose, and kyphoscoliosis.This disorder was first discovered in the summer of 1991, by D L Viljoen et al., they described three sisters all over the age of 60 with all of the symptoms described above which were similar to those in Rubenstein-Taybi syndrome. The suspected mode of inheritance is autosomal recessive.

